  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reports\n- Large cash transaction reporting\n- Cross-border money transfer monitoring\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training employees on detecting potential money laundering\n\n4. Regulatory compliance\n- Following guidelines from agencies like FinCEN\n- Adhering to international standards\n- Potential significant penalties for non-compliance\n\n5. Transaction monitoring\n- Tracking unusual financial activities\n- Identifying potential red flags\n- Reporting suspicious patterns\n\n6. Customer due diligence\n- Ongoing monitoring of customer accounts\n- Assessing risk levels\n- Updating customer information\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in substantial financial penalties and potential criminal liability.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific legal obligations?",
